comment_text_display:
If you can still find the 2024 S90D on clearance get that instead.

S90D has better color volume (BT.2020 S90D 83.4% vs S95F 79.7%) and the game mode is more punchy ("Landscape Pool" S90D 392nits vs S95F 285nits. "Yellow Skyscraper" S90D 822nits vs. S95F 708nits).
Accuracy vs vibrance can be debated but for gaming most people will take the more vibrant image.
The only place where S95F wins is on small peak highlights.

comment_text_display:
I have the 65" S95F. Black looks black to me.

The part of the S95F not having any Dirty Screen Effect is very true for my TV.

Filmmaker mode looks good if you set Picture Clarity: Custom, Judder reduction=5. Without it, panning scenes stutter. If I enable the Blur reduction setting I can bad soap opera affect.
Some people mention that Judder reduction causes artifacts in grass, but I have not noticed that, perhaps I have not looked to closely.

Contrast I turn down from 50 to 47, or else it looks a bit harsh.
Color I turn down from 25 to 24.

I kept "Peak Brightness: High" for HDR and "Peak Brightness: Medium" for SDR, these are the default settings. If I increase peak brightness for SDR, I see too much grain in the image.

I've kept the light sensor turned on, but you can disable it under General & Privacy->Power and Energy Saving->Brightness Optimization if you want to ensure max brightness.

I have my TV on a stand close to the wall. Placed like this the built-in speakers sound slightly better than I would have expected from such a thin TV.

comment_text_display: S95D owner here - coming from a Panasonic Viera Plasma (12 years old but I loved it).  In Florida, the anti-glare feature is amazing!  Also, at night we can watch movies and when people turn on a light in the kitchen, there is NO reflection.   Also, love the one connect.  With a slim fit wall mount, it looks very clean.  One wire going from TV, down the wall and into the one connect that sits in our media center/TV stand.   Paired with our Samsung Soundbar, which Q Symphony takes up a notch.    We keep in movie or filmmaker mode.  Had to turn off ALL of the smoothing as the Soap Opera effect was just too much for us coming from the older plasma.   Gaming is incredible.   I could care less about the software as we use Apple TV for everything.  I highly recommend this TV for anyone.  If you live in a house with a lot of natural light this is a no brainer.  If you, like me, watch TV when other people have lights on, this is also a no brainer.  ZERO reflection.

comment_text_display:
Great review. The S95F isn't the top flagship OLED this year, but the competition doesn't offer a clearly superior alternative. The Panasonic comes with a hefty price premium of €2,000, Sony's model is limited to 65 inches, and the LG G5 still suffers from firmware issues.
Ultimately, I hesitated between the LG G5 and the Samsung S95F, but I chose the S95F. Initially, I was put off by the matte screen, but seeing it in-store changed my perspective: it doesn't look cheap and actually handles reflections better than I expected, making me think about my tolerance for glare.
Overall, the S95F is a compelling option despite some compromises. It holds special significance for me: my first flat-screen TV was a Samsung 20 years ago. After owning a Sony, a Panasonic, and then a LG, it feels like I'm cycling through the same sequence again.
Final note: that CANVAS TV stand has a perfect design. A manufacturer should derive this concept for a central channel speaker with this form factor (or start a partnership with CANVAS).

comment_text_display:
@@RigVader The upscale is very good. The motion compensation is performing ok (i only use dejudder +2): i do not think that the other brands processing can make such a difference on that front. However I've got a 3:2 pulldown judder that is showing on some 24p content: I had to use an apple tv to circumvent that. Other things that bothered me: ugly interface, buggy HDR in Gaming mode.
So this TV is fantastic but samsung is lenient on software. Overall that's a good product but not without flaws. G5 has software problems too, Panasonic and Sony have a premium price tag. There is no clear winner.

comment_text_display: @@andrewrobinsonreviews What impressed me with this generation of OLED from Samsung is that they bridged the gap in a meaningful way to their mini LEDs in terms of brightness. When the S95D is next to the QN90D, the QN model certainly appears brighter, with white highlights far more punchy. But with the S95F next to the QN90F, white highlights appear very similar, and full screen brightness doesn't fall far behind unless most of the screen is white. The % increase between generations might be as expected, but it makes it far easier to recommend OLED

comment_text_display:
Hello !

You've correctly raised the details regarding DV, Tayzen, etc., but their global leadership positions shouldn't encourage them to change course much, lol

Seeing Netflix offering HDR10+, it's more like the market is slowly adapting to them.

I'm not a big fan of Samsung; I've always been a Sony (and a little Panasonic) fan in recent years. But I have to say that the QD OLED mix (with all its positives) and the matte-coated panel really impressed me. The blacks get deeper as light pollution decreases.

For me, blaming Samsung's coating for a lack of contrast is like blaming a movie theater for making us watch a movie in the dark, lol.

I use an Apple TV, so Tayzen doesn't bother me at all.

The main reason I'm not buying a Samsung is because the upscaling is inferior to the others (especially Sony).

YouTube channels love to rave about HDR performance, but I still watch a lot of programs in SDR, bcs I'm from Paris, and in France we don't have many TV programs (shows, movies, sports, anime) in HDR yet, I have all the Netflix, Amazon Prime or Disney+ subscriptions to have a choice, but in SDR. so it's very important.

You're going to get the B8II; it's an excellent model. Sony could have pushed the brightness further; it's way behind the competition, even though the price isn't 😅

They probably don't want to compete too much with the B9, which remains THE flagship model.

By the way, I'd like you to give us a little bit of your opinion on the market compared to what you've already tested overall, and your specific impression of the Bravia 9 and the Bravia 8 II, because I'm hesitating between the two for my next TV.

My 2020 Oled tv Sony A8H is good, but it's slowly starting to fall behind since the arrival of the Bravia 9 and the QD OLED, lol

Thank you for the complete and honest review!

comment_text_display: ⁠​⁠@@Tripokaridos22 I have used glossy OLEDs for the past 7 years, across two homes and 5 rooms. Not once have reflections been a problem for me and these were 500-800 nit TVs, much less bright and with lesser reflection handling than newer glossy TV’s in this class. That said, I have never placed my tv so that a window or naked light source was directly reflected, viewed from the sofa. I saw the S95F in the store, where indirect overhead lighting at a steep angle to the screen, made for a very grey black (!), while the glossy OLED next to it was entirely unaffected. Contrast is the main driver of picture quality and why many consider OLED superior in the first place. Why not just buy an LCD TV, if you are throwing all that away? Not saying there is not a use case for some people, but if you already apply a minimal amount of consideration in how you set your room up, I’d struggle to see the appeal. Of course I never owned one, but considering one for a light controlled man cave 😅
comment_text_original: ⁠​⁠@@Tripokaridos22 I have used glossy OLEDs for the past 7 years, across two homes and 5 rooms. Not once have reflections been a problem for me and these were 500-800 nit TVs, much less bright and with lesser reflection handling than newer glossy TV’s in this class. That said, I have never placed my tv so that a window or naked light source was directly reflected, viewed from the sofa. I saw the S95F in the store, where indirect overhead lighting at a steep angle to the screen, made for a very grey black (!), while the glossy OLED next to it was entirely unaffected. Contrast is the main driver of picture quality and why many consider OLED superior in the first place. Why not just buy an LCD TV, if you are throwing all that away? Not saying there is not a use case for some people, but if you already apply a minimal amount of consideration in how you set your room up, I’d struggle to see the appeal. Of course I never owned one, but considering one for a light controlled man cave 😅

comment_text_display: ​@oskartrotterpando8561  Woled (white OLED) is just the basic tech that was first introduced when oleds were created. At the price of most OLED these days, you're better off with the QD version (quantum dots) if you're willing to spend that much on a tv, might as well go big. Nothing wrong with the W version and it's still a good tv with nice dark to light contrasts but it might stuggle to be as bright as QLED/LCD tvs but nothing a dark room can't fix and again it's just old-ish tech compared to what's out there right now.

comment_text_display: I've had both a Samsung and LG oled. Use to own S90C and now C4 and C5. I prefer LG's color tone because its more easily adjustable. On The S90C standard was too blue and warm 1 too yellow. No middle ground. On the LGs I can go from 0 to 50 cool or 0 to 50 warm and able to dial down exactly what I want, middle ground easy to find for color tone. I also think Woled is underrated while QD is overrated. The woled looks more natural and more balanced.

comment_text_display:
Uh...the first question I have is...why are you comparing Samsung's Flagship with LG's budget Oled? I mean you should've talked about LG G5 because it is also WOLED and costs more than the S95F. At least in India it does. C5 isn't really S95F's rival, G5 is. I actually looked at both C5 and S95F side by side at the showroom trust me the difference is significant. You'll notice it instantly. The showroom I went to didn't have G5 on display so couldnt see it in person. But I've done a lil research. G5 is LG's 2025 flagship. Although if what you're trying to say is if someone's tight on budget they can absolutely go for the budget OLED, I agree. Any OLED is a massive upgrade over any LCD.

Secondly, while yeah the purple tint thingy idk. Samsung has kinda countered that problem with their matte coating. It literally eats up all the light. Now you might see raised blacks in the areas where light is getting diffused but trust me it won't break your viewing experience like reflections and like mentioned in the video, in a dark room there's just no competition.

comment_text_display:
Hm, I feel like I explain most of this in the video. 🤔 Made a comment specifically about the comparisons. But you also have to understand that the LG G5 isn't QD-OLED or W-OLED, it's Tandem OLED (aka 4-stack OLED). I didn't mention the G5 for that reason. The C5 is LG's newest W-OLED tech and the Samsung S95F is Samsungs newest QD-OLED. Peak flagships in their own category. I'm comparing the tech, not necessarily specific TV's. Only listing TV's as examples of the tech.

I also addressed in the video and explained the purple issue and how it's been largely fixed. Hope this clears it up! :) Thanks for watching! 🙏

comment_text_display:
Just to explain why QD-OLED has quicker burn in over W-OLED, basically only because of how they produce white light...
QD-OLED produces white light by turning on all three primary colors at the same time (red green blue)
W-OLED produces white light by just turning on the white pixels that it has. that's the W in W-OLED.

Not sure if you know this or not since u didn't mention the G5 at all, it is in fact still a W-OLED.

When LG swapped to deuterium and marketed their panels as EVO, they still were WOLED.

comment_text_display:
usually ... when we say " once you go ultrawide, you will never go back" ... most of the time, we talk about "ultrawide" monitor, not "super ultrawide" :D it's a bit over the top to start with a 32:9 ! :D
ofc i understand the appeal to work with a 32:9 monitor, but as you guessed it, OLED aren't really for desk work, the pixel response time and HDR capability are for gaming and movies ! that's what i did less than a year now, buying the Samsung OLED G8 ( same as yours but 21:9) and it's awesome ! it has his drawback, like, it's also a smartTV and after coming back from sleep, sometime the computer don't even know the screen is here, but from an image quality perspective, it's nearly perfect !

also, about burn in, yes, the result of Monitor Unboxed are encouraging, but a monitor is meant (usually) to be used between 5 to 10 year ! it's not something you change every year or two ! so, ok, good result for now, but as for me, i'm removing ANY KIND of wallpaper and put a pitch black background ! you see, OLED burn in are made because the pixels are used ! not because the thing are static on screen, just because they "work" ! and on an OLED, when it's black, i mean TRUE black, pixel just .... don't work at all ! it's not a technique, it's how they work, so, a black background and very agressive auto shutdown when inactive are the most powerfull tool to keep your preeeeciooooousssssss monitor alive longer !

welcome in the ultrawide family :D

comment_text_display: @@vicmanpergar same. I've been using an OLED TV with a laptop for media consumption, and it's worked very well. However, I've left it on without a screen saver a couple times, and it affected the pixels. It looked like burn-in; it's not, it's something called "image persistence" and was able to be cleared, it's a stepping stone, and a reminder that LCD derivatives simply don't have these worries.. SO... while OLED is great for these purposes, for a general monitor, Mini LED is a better solution.

comment_text_display:
So I picked up an Odyssey G9, around 2020/2021. At first I really liked the display, as it was a HUGE (literally and figuratively) improvement over my old screens. I also used an Ergotron monitor arm, and it performed amazingly well as a mount. Like you, I thought the original stand was a bit too bulky. I recall the one that came with mine was even bigger, and wider. It practically took up the entire desk. Though, I did say "at first", because I ended up selling the screen, about a year or so later. While I liked the width, it was a little too wide with the curve. I also wanted a taller screen, as I was getting a bit frustrated by the lack of vertical space. I also noticed that the dimming zones for HDR was very bad. It was (at the time) a VA panel, and the ghosting was really bad. It became super noticeable, even moving the mouse around. Then there were issues with gaming. Even with tools like Borderless Gaming (also useful for non-gaming stuff, btw), issues kept appearing. Like having HUD elements just spread all over the place, your HP all the way over to the top left, ammo all the way over to the bottom right, etc. Then there was issues relating to fan noise, and plastic creaking. These issues just kept pilling up, and figured the super ultrawide, at least not Samsungs vision of it, was not for me. So I ended up selling it for a LG C1 TV, a 48incher. Still big with tons of space, but a much... and I can't stress this enough, MUCH better display. I just swapped the stand out for a 3rd party one (smaller footprint), and it's been great. I do wish they had a 43inch (like the followup C2), but I don't regret the purchase.

EDIT: I really wouldn't worry about modern burn-in. Granted Samsung's version of OLED is worse for this, but I don't think the majority of folks need to worry. There is plenty of tools that the screens use to prevent burn-in. I've had my OLED TV now for about 4 years now, and it's been fine. Granted I do use dark mode... you light mode heathen.

comment_text_display:
I liked the perspective from the lady reviewing the Samsung 49". Her thinking was very relatable, and I think, spot on. I think she's right that an OLED Ultrawide might be unnecessary for the tasks that she does, writing, researching, etc. But she did indicate the need could be different for those who use such a monitor in a different way, such as gamers.

I am an old guy who still plays a combat MMO game (War Thunder) where my Alienware 34" Curved Ultrawide QD OLED Gaming Monitor (AW3423DWF) allows me to see clearly all the enemy aircraft as I enter the battle, their positions in all directions, up, down, right, left. My OLED allows me to see them clearly. I used to use a 35" Acer 1440p VA Curved Ultrawide, and while it worked fine for seeing the enemy, it was not as clear as my QD OLED.

Oh, having used a curved ultrawide monitor, I will never go back to a flat panel monitor. I will never go back to a monitor at 27" or less, either. Just can't see enough. Also, I'm spoiled by my QD OLED, which means my next monitor, if there is one, will have to be an OLED, as well.

comment_text_display:
I work in IT and set a couple up for C levels and have a similar monitor at home. I have a tip for machines that have issues running the full single resolution.

These monitors will all usually let you do Picture-by-Picture. So, connect your dock or PC to the monitor TWICE! Sometimes this can be a bit funky, and you WILL have multiple task bars. But it's a way to get past the single screen resolution issues that some laptop and integrated GPUs have.

The speaker issue mentioned in the video can be fixed by orienting the speakers horizontally.
comment_text_original:
I work in IT and set a couple up for C levels and have a similar monitor at home. I have a tip for machines that have issues running the full single resolution. 

These monitors will all usually let you do Picture-by-Picture. So, connect your dock or PC to the monitor TWICE! Sometimes this can be a bit funky, and you WILL have multiple task bars. But it's a way to get past the single screen resolution issues that some laptop and integrated GPUs have. 

The speaker issue mentioned in the video can be fixed by orienting the speakers horizontally.

comment_text_display:
As someone who bought an ultrawide for gaming a year or two ago, I really like it. I got a 34in 3440x1440 (only 21:9) IPS flat (no curve) panel at 144hz for $300. Personally, I feel that the 32:9 ratio is a little too extreme for gaming. On 21:9 I get a little extra peripheral vision and immersiveness in my games without things looking too warped, whereas things look really stretched and weird at the edges on a 32:9. UI elements look fine when placed at either 16:9 or 21:9 locations, but putting UI elements at the end of a 32:9 space is just silly.

As for productivity, it makes doing 2 windows side by side nicer, and it makes 3 windows side by side possible when compared to 16:9. I still have a second monitor though xd.

comment_text_display:
That's tariff pricing, got mine for sub 1000.
Here's some pro tips:
* Get the 93, not the 95. The difference is Smart TV features and latency.
* Use Mactype with the QD-OLED profile (A or B). The subpixel layout of this panel is wild without it, especially the 1440p variants benefit a lot.
* Treat the jogwheel extremely carefully, it breaks off very easily, the plastic holding it to the directional buttons is super thin.
* Clean with isopropyl. Unlike other screens, this one even demands it, and it works super well.
* If you plan to use DP with DSC, you might need an active signal extender, cause this panel sucks at not randomly black screening with compression on.

comment_text_display: I had an ultrawide for a long time. However, I found it to be an often problematic setup if you play higher-end games and use apps & programs on a second monitor normally. There were frequent resolution, screen tearing, or just flat-out nonfunctioning issues with an ultrawide. If all one does is work or play one singular game at a time without any other programs concurrently, yeah, it's fine. Otherwise, a triple monitor setup is far better for anyone serious about gaming or multitasking. One 42-inch and two 32-inch monitors are the sweet spot.

comment_text_display: I have over a dozen monitors for various purposes, and none are OLED.  Nor are my two TVs. My daily driver PC -- the one I'm using to send this comment -- uses a 32" 4K VA panel at 60Hz.  I tried using a 43" 4K TV at this station, and even though I shopped specifically for one that would not make text look awful, it wasn't great.  And it made me turn my head too much to see content.  And it died in 15 months.  I like 34" 3440x1440 monitors for gaming, but I'm sticking with 32" 4K for general use.

1440 pixels in vertical is miserable. I don’t know what you guys do — maybe just gaming — and that’s fine, but for any kind of work or creative tasks, vertical space is what really matters. We write long code, not wide code.

comment_text_display:
I love my OLED, but it's a "standard" 4k LG 48". 48" is a bit large for desktop use, but they didn't have the 42" when I bought mine (of course, they released that model the following year...) I purposely stayed away from the super-ultrawide 49" because of the way burn-in works on OLEDs, and my previous experience with a not-quite-as-super-ultrawide 34".

Since there's so little super-ultrawide content (for the 34" or 49" varieties), a lot of content will be displayed pillar-boxed. This ages the pixels in the center moreso than on the outside. With OLEDs, the more wear you have ona given pixel, the dimmer it will get. With prolonged use, this means the central pixels will get dimmer than those on the outside. Given that on super-ultrawides, you're using those central pixels more, just due to the way most content is formatted, there's going to be more wear on the pixels in that center section, and it's going to get dimmer a bit faster. You'll probably only really notice it when you do watch/edit super-ultrawide content, though, since that's when you'll have the same content going across those boundaries.

I'm assuming that anti-burn tech has gotten a bit better in the 5-ish years since I got mine and did my research as well, so YMMV.

With that said, I do think the 34" was a better format for productivity, and I can see how the 49" could be even better. Just be careful of placing static content in the same place all the time, and make sure to enable the burn-prevention features where you can.

comment_text_display:
I had a 49" ultrawide for...a week. It seemed like such a great idea, replacing three (1440p and 2 x 1080p) of my four monitors with one continuous space. In reality, I actually lost screen real estate...which I could've lived with, but the fact that no horizontal line was straight frankly broke my brain even while coding; trying to do 3D modelling was just impossible. The fact that you have to be viewing it from a single point in space without moving in order to make it work (physically impossible for all human beings with two functioning eyes) just meant the whole thing was a waste of time. It went back as soon as I realised my error in judgement.

Great for gaming, awful for everything else.

comment_text_display: I bought my G9 nearly 2 years ago on a black Friday and i love it. Now ... i will say that love comes always with some compromises and using an ultrawide monitor is no different, for example: 1. I rarely see media optimized for this resolution, regardless if it's a video, a wallpaper or a game you will have to deal with either playing or watching something in Window Mode or seeing 2 black bars on each side. Wallpapers are also hard to come by, but these days with AI you can ask it to fill in the gaps and it's not so bad. Now i will say for games that do support it, example Mechwarrior, its was G-L-O-R-I-O-U-S i felt i was inside of that war machine shooting other mechs. 2. Like shown in the video, getting used to snap windows in place is not an easy task, until you find a software that makes "virtual windows" that you can snap your browser in that place. In Windows you have Microsoft powertoy FancyFences, in Linux, you have a Gnome Tiling shell extension and macOS .. no idea :). 3. If you need to share your screen in a team meeting and if the other person doesn't have an ultrawide screen ... your in for a treat, the person on the other side wont be able to see anything because you are looking at a ultrawide resolution on a smaller screen.. I found that on Windows you can use "Region To Share", Linux i don't know :) and macOS ZoneShare should do the trick. So instead you choosing the entire screen, you open and choose that app and will work as if you have a monitor inside of a monitor. In my case i snap Region to Share into a pre-defined FanzyZones i created for sharing my screen ....

comment_text_display:
I have the 57" version of that monitor it's about a year and a half old now... Yours is probably an updated version.... Here's my opinion.
1) the curve is too sharp.
2) the layout is just a little too wide. Instead of a 32:9 dual 4k display or the 32:9 dual 1440p that I use mine at a 32:12 or dual 4:3 would be better. It would increase the pixel count by ⅓. This means that the 5120×1440 would be 5120×1920. For the 1440p setting, and 10240÷3840. And if you remember the old 1024×768 4:3 monitors it starts to make even more sense.
3) it's really heavy and make sure you get a monitor arm that's actually strong enough, and never throw away the box or Styrofoam packing materials because if you ever have to take it apart you don't want the glass to break because it bent too much

Perhaps you can give a 32" oled a shot, or maybe get a review unit you can try out. I'm sure you can still use a 2nd vertical monitor with this setup. 32" oled at 1440p is kinda low (looks like 1080p at that screen size) but at least you know your laptop will be able to run it at decent fps, vs a 4k model.

Though like you mentioned, a laptop or desktop upgrade is certainly in the future.

comment_text_display: Ja, das 2025er QD-OLED setzt auf eine 5-Stack-Struktur (3× Blau + 2× Grün), was Effizienz und Spitzenhelligkeit steigert. Beim S95F sind die HDMI-2.1-Ports auf 40 Gbps limitiert (4K/165 Hz via DSC), und die Glare-Free-Beschichtung streut Licht stark—QD-OLEDs können je nach Lichtsituation eine leicht violette Tönung zeigen.

comment_text_display:
Kein schlechter Fernseher, aber das Samsung sich weigert Dolby Vision zu nutzen, weil sie lieber HDR10+ pushen wollen (welches sie selbst mitentwickelt haben) ist einfach schwach. Dolby Vision hat sich schon komplett durchgesetzt bei 4K Discs (die haben Alternativ meist nur HDR10 mit auf der Scheibe) und den meisten Streamingdiensten. Hier hat nur Amazon HDR10+ zu bieten bzw. bietet nur das an (soweit ich weiß) und das auch nur, weil sie ebenfalls an der Entwicklung beteiligt sind.
Ich bleib lieber bei Herstellern, die mir alle möglichen Darstellungsvarianten bieten und nicht eines vorschreiben wollen.

comment_text_display:
Dann werde ich dich hiermit mal aufklären

Das einbrennen in OLED Displays ist praktisch unmöglich. Es gibt seit mindestens vier Jahren Präventivmethoden, dass ein einbrennen eines OLED Einfach unmöglich macht.

Wenn du dir tatsächlich ein QLED gekauft hast, weil ein OLED sich einbrennen kann, dann hast du einen absolut großen Fehler gemacht

Ich besitze ein OLE vom Jahr 2021 den Sony A 80 J Diesel OLE. Fernseher hat ein Pixel Shift System, was nach dem Ausschalten des Fernsehers beginnt. Demzufolge hat er Präventivmaßnahmen, das ein brennenden, praktisch unmöglich macht.

Ich bin ein Hardcorezocker. Das bedeutet innerhalb von einem Jahr mache ich über 1000 Stunden im Ego Shooter Bereich. Insgesamt sind das wahrscheinlich 1500 Stunden zocken im Jahr
Und dann erklär mir mal bitte, wo sich mein Fernseher eingebrannt hat

Nur Menschen, die keine Ahnung haben, behaupten, dass OLED Fernseher einbrennen und man deswegen ein QLED Fernseher kaufen soll
Die Qualitäts Einbußen, die du da machst, weil du dir kein OLED Fernseher gekauft hast, sind schon enorm und ich spreche aus Erfahrung weil ich habe mir 2018 ein Q LED Fernseher gekauft, nämlich der Q9fn
Der bis dato hellste Quantum Dott Fernseher

Bitte recherchiere und gucke dir auf YouTube Videos an, was Burn in beim OLED tatsächlich bedeutet
Es ist nur theoretisch möglich. Praktisch ist es unmöglich.

comment_text_display:
I ordered an open box 77" LG C4 from Best Buy for $1300 and they gave me a 77" Samsung S95D. I didn't realize it until I got home. Trying to decide if I want to keep it or return it. I think I might keep it. I don't feel like hauling this sucker back 😅
Update:
After having the S95D for a week I'm keeping it! It's definitely an upgrade from my 77" LG CX. It was basically a brand new tv all the accessories were still wrapped and the screen still had the plastic film on it. And the Xbox app was a pleasant surprise since I already have Xbox Ultimate.
The matte coating doesn't bother me, the blacks still look perfect to me.

comment_text_display: Factually, if you are a purest, the LG G5 does things that are simply not acceptable. Oversharpening that leaves an unnatural picture, huge problems with posterisation, and a new panel tech that leaves alot of dithering when close up. Everyone can deny these problems and that’s fine, but the problems are there for all to see. Out of the flagship offerings from the main four manufacturers, the LG G5 has the most problems, and offers on the whole the objectively worst image quality. But if everyone loves their purchase, that’s a good thing. If you don’t notice these things, that’s again is a good thing

comment_text_display:
If it's the display video, that test really only applies for performance in a very dark or dim room and only assessed only mainly the TVs performed in staying faithful to the creator's intent for movies. I'd say unless you're a movie enthusiast who must absolutely have the most accurate image, Rtings' comparison is way more relevant to the average consumer. Plus the TVs were professionally calibrated to their most accurate Filmmaker mode which typically produces quite a dim presentation which most people do not like.
That being said, the Panasonic sounds really good if you can actually buy it outside of America given Panasonic's TV division is on life support.

comment_text_display:
Hey there! That's right, Sony officially recommend that calibrators use the CIE170-2:2015 CMF, but if their equipment doesn't support that, Sony recommends using the Judd modified color matching function with an alternate white point, instead of the industry-standard D65.

We took additional measurements with both of these alternative calibration methods. When measured against CIE170-2, our unit is actually a bit less accurate than the official results in the review.

When we use the same CIE1931 CMF but with the Judd white point instead, the BRAVIA 8 II is much more accurate than the official results in our review. Since we aim for a fair comparison between every TV we test, we left the results with the CIE1931 CMF and the D65 white point in the review, but we have the results relative to the Judd white point over on our website under the SDR Pre-Calibration Color Accuracy score!
comment_text_original:
Hey there! That's right, Sony officially recommend that calibrators use the CIE170-2:2015 CMF, but if their equipment doesn't support that, Sony recommends using the Judd modified color matching function with an alternate white point, instead of the industry-standard D65.

We took additional measurements with both of these alternative calibration methods. When measured against CIE170-2, our unit is actually a bit less accurate than the official results in the review.

When we use the same CIE1931 CMF but with the Judd white point instead,  the BRAVIA 8 II is much more accurate than the official results in our review. Since we aim for a fair comparison between every TV we test, we left the results with the CIE1931 CMF and the D65 white point in the review, but we have the results relative to the Judd white point over on our website under the SDR Pre-Calibration Color Accuracy score!

comment_text_display: Well, I'm looking for a TV that will serve solely as a PC gaming TV. I had an S95D for a year, and although the matte finish isn't as bad as some people say, I prefer a glossy finish. So, unfortunately, Samsung is out of the question. It's a shame that Samsung tries to force people to be happy without giving them a choice. I'll probably buy the G5, which is glossy, but it also has its drawbacks (dithering and poorer colors). It's a shame that Samsung, due to its policy, wastes the potential of the QD OLED panel (I'm not counting the Sony because I have an A95L for movies and now I'm looking for something just for gaming), which has so many advantages and is perfect for gaming thanks to its colors.

comment_text_display: The real competitor to the Samsung S95F is not the LG G5, but the LG M5, which is a G5 with a remote box containing all mandatory connectors, like the S95F. Then, a very important thing to notice (yet unnoticed in all reviews) is that Samsung's One Connect Box has become a low-profile, thin (shallow height) but huge (WxD) 'pizza box' that doesn't fit inside many TV cabinets anymore, including |kea's! Which makes the “you can place it anywhere” comment at 11:48 rather comical. Whereas LG's Zero Connect box is much thicker, but its width and depth are rather limited, allowing it to fit into any furniture. This is such an important parameter to know when you've decided to buy this kind of TV to hang on the wall. Speaking of real-world practicality for real-world users.

comment_text_display: ​@@LXBattiatus A small one yes, in a small appartement. Not everyone lives in countries with gigantic houses. With the cables behind, the One Connect Box needs about 35-36 cm in depth to fit. And it can't be turned 90°, as it's also 36 cm long. The problem is such that it has a dedicated thread on Reddit. On the contrary, LG's Zero Connect Box has a square footprint 23 cm each side. In the past, Samsung didn't make the same mistake. For example, Samsung Q9F, Q90R, Q95T had a long, thick remote box with very little depth that fitted even in small cabinets.

comment_text_display: They weighed SDR and HDR 50/50 whereas Rtings does 70%HDR 30%SDR which I think is a better weighted system. Also the Value Electronics shootout the TV's were compared to reference, not each other- so having 700+nits SDR brightness is actually worse than 400 nit brightness when the content is supposed to be 100nits. The TV's were also calibrated in the VE shootout whereas they aren't calibrated here and thus the Sony is performing much worse in rtings review than the shootout. Depends on what you value. All are great TV's and unless you see them side-by-side none of us would probably be able to notice these minor differences.

comment_text_display: I always appreciate these product comparison videos! I just wanted to mention that when choosing between these two models, buyers should consider an additional factor that affects how these TVs perform in a bright room. While it's true that the matte screen of the Samsung S95F handles DIRECT reflections better than the glossy G5, in a room with bright ambient light, the Samsung is susceptible to "black level rise". That means the quantum dots in the S95F re-radiate the light in a bright room, causing the perfect blacks of the screen to become gray. That would be a deal breaker for me. When I buy an OLED TV, I want a screen that maintains perfect blacks, even in a bright room (like the LG G5).

comment_text_display: A significant issue with WOLED is the inescapable greenish-blue push. Virtually all WOLED panels exhibit a faint veil of green/blue that permeates the image at all times. This cannot be calibrated out, as it is inherent to the technology and caused by the white sub-pixel. Once you see it, you cannot unsee it. If you’re skeptical, watch any side-by-side comparison between a QD-OLED and a WOLED. Pay close attention to scenes with white, clouds, water, or other light-colored scenery. The tint becomes immediately apparent, and once noticed, you will detect it in virtually every color. I’m amazed this is so rarely discussed, as it is a very real, easily visible problem. The most effective way to spot it is to pause a comparison on a white screen, snow, clouds, etc.

comment_text_display: ​@@captaincrunch7944QD-OLED is definitely better than WOLED because it uses red, green, and blue subpixel structure rather than red, green, blue, and white like WOLED. Honestly, I wish plasma TVs had continued to advance. Just like OLED, they use emissive pixel technology; however, each pixel was a tiny glass capsule filled with noble gases that would glow when excited with electricity. The glowing incandescent light output of plasma is vastly superior to the LED light output of OLED and Mini-LED. Plasma produced colors that were much richer and more impactful, reminiscent of an oil painting. It's interesting because OLED has a wider color gamut coverage than plasma; however, plasma has more continuous bands of light across the visible spectrum. On a CIE chart, OLED and Mini-LED show tall, narrow spectral spikes, meaning their light output is concentrated at specific wavelengths, which makes color production a bit harsh and unnatural. Plasma has very smooth, broad, overlapping spectral curves on a CIE chart due to its glowing phosphors. As a result, color production is much more natural and cinematic. A last-gen high-end plasma will still destroy the very best OLED has to offer, but there is a big caveat... only in a dark room environment. Plasma just cannot get very bright, and all of that magic disappears in a bright room. It's unfortunate because it was such a perfect TV technology.

comment_text_display:
15:30 I would say that is more of an UK issue than a Samsung issue. Companies will try to get away with whatever the country let them to.
In Australia I bought my first 4k TV in 2015... then in 2016, the screen started to show some issues. Samsung replaced the model free of charge with their new equivalent 2016 model... 2 years later, in 2018, a new problem started happening with the panel.. they again, free of charge, replaced my 2016 TV with their new 2018 model. So I got free TV upgrades twice. I couldn't complain about Samsung service at all. They surely didn't let me down. The 2018 TV never gave me any problem, but now I want to upgrade to a more modern and bigger TV, which is why I'm watching this.

comment_text_display: I know right? Especially for sdr. Your eyes can see a much broader range of brightness and color than reference SDR. Juice up that SDR image. What I am concerned about is which configuration provides the most natural looking image. For the most part, that will be the most immersive experience. Although there are movies, like that Matrix, which is intended to have a greenish tint. That does provide a certain eerie vibe where I think the creators intent might be the best experience. I am kind of split on the whole argument, but I lean a little more into whichever image the viewer prefers.

Le Black Friday en Novembre va aider en ce sens.

comment_text_display:
Comme chaque année, je trouve qu’ils ont la meilleure image, la calibration est vraiment superbe pour le cinéphile que je suis. Mais qui dit cinéphile dit : ton système son moyen je veux pas le payer, merci de ne pas enlaidir cette dalle avec cette""barre"" de son, j’a déjà un système. Leur "étude" sur ce que veux le consommateur, en salon impossible d’avoir de détail la dessus, même le représentant en salon, à longueur de journée avoue devoir dire « non cela n’existent pas sans la barre son intégré », chaque année c’est pareil (c’est vrai le public salon n’est pas le grand public, quoique). Pour rappel en 2022 ils étaient la seule marque en recul de vente de près de 23% sur l’OLED…
Puis ces bordures désolé en 2025 sur un tel haut de gamme c’est pas possible, à ce prix ça doit être borderless, soyons exigeant ! Puis QUE deux sorties HDMI 2.1, non mais là ! Franchement, j’en ai 4 bah je suis bien content de les avoir !! Même si j ai un ampli denon avec pleins de sortie, c’est important.
Voilà voilà 😅
Mais bon la calibration panasonic et leur traitement video fera toujours battre mon cœur ❤
Merci PP 🙏🏻

comment_text_display: Un point qui est rarement abordé dans les tests, car impossible à mesurer à très court terme : la fiabilité des produits. Selon moi Panasonic, si les produits actuels sont comme les anciens, est la marque de téléviseurs la plus fiable du marché. Nous possédons chez mes grands-parents une TV Panasonic écran plasma de 2004, qui refuse décemment de rendre l’âme. Je n’ai jamais rien vu de tel pour un téléviseur. Je serai immensément triste si la distribution des produits Pana venait à changer ces prochaines années en Europe, car pas assez de ventes. Pour ceux qui ont déjà eu une Pana, c’est très difficile d’avoir un autre téléviseur, idem pour leurs autres produits d’ailleurs.
